        <h2 class="text-4xl lg:text-[60px] font-black leading-[1.1] mb-3">re-enchantment</h2>
        <svg class="w-24 lg:w-32 h-6 mb-6" viewBox="0 0 120 20" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <path d="M2 10C6 4 10 4 14 10C18 16 22 16 26 10C30 4 34 4 38 10C42 16 46 16 50 10C54 4 58 4 62 10C66 16 70 16 74 10C78 4 82 4 86 10C90 16 94 16 98 10C102 4 106 4 110 10C114 16 118 16 118 10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
        </svg>
        <div class="text-sm lg:text-[15px] font-semibold leading-[1.5] max-w-[480px]">
          <p>
            By re-enchantment I refer not to a nostalgic return to "magic," but to
            contemporary efforts to counter Weberian "disenchantment" by resto-
            ring a felt sense of liveliness, relationality, and mystery in human–world
            relations without abandoning critical thought. Scholars in environmen-
            tal humanities describe re-enchantment as a way of unsettling modern
            notions of a dead, mute world, foregrounding instead the affective and
            ethical force of vibrant, more-than-human ecologies.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

